[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there a way to convert <code>j \\leq n</code> of type <code>Nat</code> to an element of <code>Fin n</code>?</p>",
        "id": 459760244,
        "sender_full_name": "jsodd",
        "timestamp": 1723323835
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Example: I have a vector <code>x : Fin i \\to R</code>, where <code>i \\leq n</code>, and I want to extend it by zero by <code>y : Fin n \\to R := fun j \\map if j \\leq i then x j else 0</code>. This doesn't work because <code>x</code> doesn't accept <code>j</code> of type <code>Nat</code>.</p>",
        "id": 459760591,
        "sender_full_name": "jsodd",
        "timestamp": 1723323980
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What if <code>j = n</code>? The maximum value of <code>Fin n</code> is <code>n - 1</code></p>",
        "id": 459762024,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1723324618
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, I see. The question 1 easily changes to \"is there a way to convert <code>j \\leq n-1</code> of type <code>Nat</code> to an element of type <code>Fin n</code>.</p>",
        "id": 459762813,
        "sender_full_name": "jsodd",
        "timestamp": 1723324947
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I'm actually more interested in the question from the example</p>",
        "id": 459762828,
        "sender_full_name": "jsodd",
        "timestamp": 1723324962
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe I'm doing something wrong and there is a more natural way to extend a vector by zeros?</p>",
